case of the Old Bailey in London, which formed part of the early medieval outer wall of the city."]},{"name":"Ballay","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jean-Pierre.  German Wolfgang.","Hungarian: variant of <b>Ballai</b>, a habitational name for someone from any of several places called Balla, e.g. in Heves County in the north of Hungary.","French and Breton: variant of   Balay  ."]}]},{"name":"Godefroy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French: from the personal name <i>Godefroy</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Godafrid</i>, composed of the elements <i>god</i> ‘god’ and <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. This surname is also found in England, where it is of Huguenot origin. Compare   Godfroy  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Godfroy","meanings":["From the Old French name <i>Godefroy</i>, which is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>god</i> ‘god’ (or <i>gōd</i> ‘good’) + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. This was adopted by the Normans, and brought to England by immigrants from the Low Countries and France. It was borne by a Norman saint (  <i>c.</i>1066–1115 ) who became bishop of Amiens. There has been considerable confusion with   Geoffrey ."]},{"name":"Goffin","meanings":["Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): metonymic occupational from German <i>Hopfen</i> ‘hops’. The initial <i>g</i> is due to Russian influence, since Russian has no <i>h</i> and alters it to <i>g</i> in borrowed words and names.","French and Walloon: from a pet form of the personal name   Godefroy  .","French and Walloon: possibly also a nickname from a diminutive of Old French <i>goffe</i> ‘heavy, coarse’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Godefroy de Bavay III was born in 1087, in France, his father, Godeffroy II DE BAVAY, was 37 and his mother, Gertrude D'HIRSON, was 22. He had at least 1 daughter with Jeanne de Bavay. He died in 1151, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1087–1151":"1087–1151","1085–1137":"1085–1137","1090–Female"